LeetCode 21 – Merge Two Sorted Lists is a classic Linked List problem. Since you're preparing for coding tests, this one is very common in CoCubes / placement assessments.

🧠 Problem

You are given two sorted linked lists list1 and list2.

Merge them into one sorted linked list and return the head of the merged list.

Example
Input:
list1 = [1,2,4]
list2 = [1,3,4]

Output:
[1,1,2,3,4,4]
✅ Approach (Iterative – Best for Placements)

Idea:

Create a dummy node to start the merged list.

Compare nodes from both lists.

Attach the smaller node to the result list.

Move the pointer forward.

If one list ends, attach the remaining nodes of the other list.

Time Complexity

O(n + m)

Space Complexity

O(1)
💻 Java Solution (Full Code for LeetCode)
class Solution {
    public ListNode mergeTwoLists(ListNode list1, ListNode list2) {
        
        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(-1);
        ListNode current = dummy;

        while(list1 != null && list2 != null){

            if(list1.val <= list2.val){
                current.next = list1;
                list1 = list1.next;
            } else {
                current.next = list2;
                list2 = list2.next;
            }

            current = current.next;
        }

        if(list1 != null){
            current.next = list1;
        } else {
            current.next = list2;
        }

        return dummy.next;
    }
}
📊 Dry Run
list1 = 1 → 2 → 4
list2 = 1 → 3 → 4

Steps:

compare 1 and 1 → add 1
compare 2 and 1 → add 1
compare 2 and 3 → add 2
compare 4 and 3 → add 3
compare 4 and 4 → add 4
add remaining 4

Result:

1 → 1 → 2 → 3 → 4 → 4
🔁 Recursive Solution (Short but Less Preferred)
class Solution {
    public ListNode mergeTwoLists(ListNode list1, ListNode list2) {

        if(list1 == null) return list2;
        if(list2 == null) return list1;

        if(list1.val < list2.val){
            list1.next = mergeTwoLists(list1.next, list2);
            return list1;
        } else {
            list2.next = mergeTwoLists(list1, list2.next);
            return list2;
        }
    }
}
